1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:02,640
You do it constantly. You tap "I

2
00:00:02,640 --> 00:00:05,280
agree." You do not read it —

3
00:00:05,280 --> 00:00:07,921
almost no one does . And buried

4
00:00:07,921 --> 00:00:10,561
in that fine print, again and again,

5
00:00:10,561 --> 00:00:13,201
is a single clause that can quietly

6
00:00:13,201 --> 00:00:15,841
take away two of your most basic

7
00:00:15,841 --> 00:00:18,482
legal rights: the right to take the

8
00:00:18,482 --> 00:00:21,122
company to court, and the right to

9
00:00:21,122 --> 00:00:23,762
join with everyone else they treated the

10
00:00:23,762 --> 00:00:26,402
same way . In 2011, a fight

11
00:00:26,402 --> 00:00:29,043
over about thirty
dollars turned that clause

12
00:00:29,043 --> 00:00:31,683
into the law of the land .

13
00:00:32,137 --> 00:00:35,282
The clause is an arbitration agreement. It

14
00:00:35,282 --> 00:00:38,428
says that if you have a dispute,

15
00:00:38,428 --> 00:00:41,573
you will not sue in a public

16
00:00:41,573 --> 00:00:44,719
court — you will take it to

17
00:00:44,719 --> 00:00:47,864
a private arbitrator, one customer at a

18
00:00:47,864 --> 00:00:51,010
time. And it usually adds a second

19
00:00:51,010 --> 00:00:54,155
piece: a class-action
waiver, a promise that

20
00:00:54,155 --> 00:00:57,301
you will never band together with other

21
00:00:57,301 --> 00:01:00,446
people who were harmed the same way

22
00:01:00,446 --> 00:01:03,592
. This is one of the most

23
00:01:03,592 --> 00:01:06,737
consequential and most
argued-about features of modern

24
00:01:06,737 --> 00:01:09,883
American law, and
reasonable people strongly disagree

25
00:01:09,883 --> 00:01:13,029
about whether it is fair. Over the

26
00:01:13,029 --> 00:01:16,174
next twelve minutes:
the thirty-dollar case that

27
00:01:16,174 --> 00:01:19,320
made it enforceable,
what the Court actually

28
00:01:19,320 --> 00:01:22,465
decided, and the honest arguments on both

29
00:01:22,465 --> 00:01:22,914
sides.

30
00:01:23,368 --> 00:01:26,587
It starts with a couple in California,

31
00:01:26,587 --> 00:01:29,806
Vincent and Liza Concepcion. They sign up

32
00:01:29,806 --> 00:01:33,025
with AT&T for
cellphones advertised as "free."

33
00:01:33,025 --> 00:01:36,244
Then the bill comes, and they have

34
00:01:36,244 --> 00:01:39,463
been charged about thirty dollars in sales

35
00:01:39,463 --> 00:01:42,222
tax on those "free" phones .

36
00:01:42,676 --> 00:01:45,768
Thirty dollars. On its own, it is

37
00:01:45,768 --> 00:01:48,860
nothing — no lawyer on earth takes

38
00:01:48,860 --> 00:01:51,952
a thirty-dollar case. And that is exactly

39
00:01:51,952 --> 00:01:55,044
the point that makes this story matter.

40
00:01:55,044 --> 00:01:58,136
Because the Concepcions were not the only

41
00:01:58,136 --> 00:02:01,228
customer charged that tax. If a company

42
00:02:01,228 --> 00:02:04,320
charges thirty dollars too much to one

43
00:02:04,320 --> 00:02:07,412
person, it is a rounding error. If

44
00:02:07,412 --> 00:02:10,504
it charges thirty dollars too much to

45
00:02:10,504 --> 00:02:13,596
millions of people, it is tens of

46
00:02:13,596 --> 00:02:16,688
millions of dollars — and now it

47
00:02:16,688 --> 00:02:18,455
is worth fighting .

48
00:02:18,909 --> 00:02:21,949
The tool for that fight is the

49
00:02:21,949 --> 00:02:24,988
class action: a
single lawsuit that bundles

50
00:02:24,988 --> 00:02:28,028
together everyone with
the same small claim,

51
00:02:28,028 --> 00:02:31,068
so that harms too tiny to sue

52
00:02:31,068 --> 00:02:34,107
over individually can be challenged all at

53
00:02:34,107 --> 00:02:37,147
once. The Concepcions wanted to bring one

54
00:02:37,147 --> 00:02:37,581
.

55
00:02:38,035 --> 00:02:41,873
But their AT&T contract said no. It

56
00:02:41,873 --> 00:02:45,710
required any dispute to go to individual

57
00:02:45,710 --> 00:02:49,548
arbitration, and it
specifically waived class actions

58
00:02:49,548 --> 00:02:53,385
. So the legal question became: is

59
00:02:53,385 --> 00:02:57,223
that waiver enforceable?
California had a rule

60
00:02:57,223 --> 00:03:01,060
— from a case called Discover Bank

61
00:03:01,060 --> 00:03:04,898
— that treated
these class-action waivers in

62
00:03:04,898 --> 00:03:08,735
consumer contracts as
unconscionable, and refused to

63
00:03:08,735 --> 00:03:12,573
enforce them. Under
California law, the Concepcions

64
00:03:12,573 --> 00:03:15,862
could keep their class action .

65
00:03:16,316 --> 00:03:19,012
AT&T argued that California rule had to

66
00:03:19,012 --> 00:03:21,709
give way to a much older federal

67
00:03:21,709 --> 00:03:24,405
law. And so a dispute over thirty

68
00:03:24,405 --> 00:03:27,102
dollars in phone tax became a case

69
00:03:27,102 --> 00:03:29,799
about who gets to decide whether you

70
00:03:29,799 --> 00:03:32,495
can ever join a class action at

71
00:03:32,495 --> 00:03:32,880
all.

72
00:03:33,334 --> 00:03:37,129
To understand the case, you have to

73
00:03:37,129 --> 00:03:40,924
understand two things: a 1925 law, and

74
00:03:40,924 --> 00:03:43,092
one small, powerful sentence.

75
00:03:43,546 --> 00:03:46,844
The 1925 law is the Federal Arbitration

76
00:03:46,844 --> 00:03:50,142
Act. It was passed to make arbitration

77
00:03:50,142 --> 00:03:53,440
agreements enforceable, reflecting
a federal policy that

78
00:03:53,440 --> 00:03:56,738
favors arbitration — the idea that if

79
00:03:56,738 --> 00:04:00,036
two parties agree
to resolve disputes privately,

80
00:04:00,036 --> 00:04:03,334
courts should hold them to it .

81
00:04:03,334 --> 00:04:06,632
For most of its life, that law

82
00:04:06,632 --> 00:04:09,930
lived quietly. Then
companies began writing arbitration

83
00:04:09,930 --> 00:04:13,228
clauses into the
everyday contracts ordinary people

84
00:04:13,228 --> 00:04:16,526
sign — for phones, banks, credit cards,

85
00:04:16,526 --> 00:04:17,939
and jobs .

86
00:04:18,393 --> 00:04:21,087
And here is what makes them so

87
00:04:21,087 --> 00:04:23,780
easy to miss. You do not sign

88
00:04:23,780 --> 00:04:26,474
these clauses with a pen at a

89
00:04:26,474 --> 00:04:29,168
desk. You accept them by activating a

90
00:04:29,168 --> 00:04:31,861
phone, opening an account, clicking a box,

91
00:04:31,861 --> 00:04:34,555
or showing up for your first day

92
00:04:34,555 --> 00:04:37,248
of work. The law treats that as

93
00:04:37,248 --> 00:04:39,942
a real agreement — and for the

94
00:04:39,942 --> 00:04:42,635
most part, the terms are not up

95
00:04:42,635 --> 00:04:45,329
for negotiation. It is take it or

96
00:04:45,329 --> 00:04:48,022
leave it, and "leaving it" can mean

97
00:04:48,022 --> 00:04:50,716
going without the service, or the job

98
00:04:50,716 --> 00:04:51,101
.

99
00:04:51,555 --> 00:04:54,800
The powerful sentence
is the class-action waiver.

100
00:04:54,800 --> 00:04:58,044
Arbitration by itself
just changes the venue

101
00:04:58,044 --> 00:05:01,289
— court versus a private arbitrator. The

102
00:05:01,289 --> 00:05:04,534
waiver does something
more: it forces every

103
00:05:04,534 --> 00:05:07,779
claim to be brought one person at

104
00:05:07,779 --> 00:05:11,024
a time. And for the small, scattered

105
00:05:11,024 --> 00:05:14,269
harms we just described, "one person at

106
00:05:14,269 --> 00:05:17,514
a time" can mean, in practice, "no

107
00:05:17,514 --> 00:05:20,758
one at all," because no individual claim

108
00:05:20,758 --> 00:05:23,540
is large enough to pursue .

109
00:05:23,994 --> 00:05:27,542
This is where honest people split, and

110
00:05:27,542 --> 00:05:31,090
it is worth hearing both sides plainly.

111
00:05:31,090 --> 00:05:34,638
Critics argue that
mandatory arbitration with class-action

112
00:05:34,638 --> 00:05:38,186
waivers — what
they call "forced arbitration"

113
00:05:38,186 --> 00:05:41,734
— can quietly close the courthouse door,

114
00:05:41,734 --> 00:05:45,282
leaving widespread small
harms with no realistic

115
00:05:45,282 --> 00:05:48,830
remedy, decided in
private proceedings that set

116
00:05:48,830 --> 00:05:50,858
no public precedent .

117
00:05:51,312 --> 00:05:54,813
Defenders argue the
opposite: that arbitration is

118
00:05:54,813 --> 00:05:58,314
generally faster, cheaper,
and less formal than

119
00:05:58,314 --> 00:06:01,816
a lawsuit, that the 1925 law reflects

120
00:06:01,816 --> 00:06:05,317
a long-standing policy
of honoring agreements people

121
00:06:05,317 --> 00:06:08,818
make, and that
individual claimants can sometimes

122
00:06:08,818 --> 00:06:12,319
do as well or better than they

123
00:06:12,319 --> 00:06:15,821
would in a crowded court . Those

124
00:06:15,821 --> 00:06:19,322
empirical claims — about cost, speed, and

125
00:06:19,322 --> 00:06:22,823
outcomes — are genuinely disputed, and we

126
00:06:22,823 --> 00:06:26,325
are not going to pretend one side

127
00:06:26,325 --> 00:06:29,826
has settled them. The case is about

128
00:06:29,826 --> 00:06:30,826
who decides.

129
00:06:31,280 --> 00:06:34,786
In 2011, the Supreme Court sided with

130
00:06:34,786 --> 00:06:38,292
AT&T. By a vote of five to

131
00:06:38,292 --> 00:06:41,798
four, it held that the Federal Arbitration

132
00:06:41,798 --> 00:06:45,304
Act preempts California's rule — that a

133
00:06:45,304 --> 00:06:48,810
state cannot refuse
to enforce a class-action

134
00:06:48,810 --> 00:06:52,316
waiver just because it finds the waiver

135
00:06:52,316 --> 00:06:55,822
unfair. If the
contract says individual arbitration,

136
00:06:55,822 --> 00:06:58,326
individual arbitration it is .

137
00:06:58,780 --> 00:07:02,284
The opinion was written by Justice Antonin

138
00:07:02,284 --> 00:07:05,787
Scalia. A state rule that singles out

139
00:07:05,787 --> 00:07:09,291
arbitration's class-action waivers
and blocks them, he

140
00:07:09,291 --> 00:07:12,795
reasoned, stands as an obstacle to the

141
00:07:12,795 --> 00:07:16,299
federal policy favoring
arbitration, and so it

142
00:07:16,299 --> 00:07:19,802
cannot stand. The federal law wins .

143
00:07:20,256 --> 00:07:22,939
Justice Stephen Breyer
wrote the dissent, and

144
00:07:22,939 --> 00:07:25,623
it put the other half of the

145
00:07:25,623 --> 00:07:28,306
problem into words. For claims worth only

146
00:07:28,306 --> 00:07:30,989
a few dollars each, he argued, the

147
00:07:30,989 --> 00:07:33,672
class action is often the only realistic

148
00:07:33,672 --> 00:07:36,355
way to hold a large company accountable

149
00:07:36,355 --> 00:07:39,039
at all. Take it away, and you

150
00:07:39,039 --> 00:07:41,722
have not just changed the forum —

151
00:07:41,722 --> 00:07:44,405
you may have ended the case before

152
00:07:44,405 --> 00:07:45,555
it starts .

153
00:07:46,009 --> 00:07:49,382
That five-to-four split did not settle the

154
00:07:49,382 --> 00:07:52,755
country's mind, but it settled the law.

155
00:07:52,755 --> 00:07:56,128
And seven years later, the Court extended

156
00:07:56,128 --> 00:07:59,502
it into the one place most adults

157
00:07:59,502 --> 00:08:02,875
spend their days: work. In Epic Systems

158
00:08:02,875 --> 00:08:06,248
v. Lewis, in 2018, by another five-to-four

159
00:08:06,248 --> 00:08:09,621
vote, with Justice
Neil Gorsuch writing, the

160
00:08:09,621 --> 00:08:12,994
Court held that
employers, too, can require

161
00:08:12,994 --> 00:08:16,367
employees to arbitrate
individually and waive class

162
00:08:16,367 --> 00:08:19,740
or collective actions — and that doing

163
00:08:19,740 --> 00:08:23,114
so does not violate federal labor law

164
00:08:23,114 --> 00:08:26,487
. The same logic that governed your

165
00:08:26,487 --> 00:08:29,378
phone contract now governed your job.

166
00:08:29,832 --> 00:08:32,910
Epic was not a quiet decision either.

167
00:08:32,910 --> 00:08:35,988
Justice Ruth Bader
Ginsburg wrote a forceful

168
00:08:35,988 --> 00:08:39,066
dissent, arguing that
forcing employees to face

169
00:08:39,066 --> 00:08:42,144
their employer one at a time ignored

170
00:08:42,144 --> 00:08:45,222
the very reason federal law lets workers

171
00:08:45,222 --> 00:08:48,300
act together — and she read part

172
00:08:48,300 --> 00:08:51,378
of it aloud from the bench, a

173
00:08:51,378 --> 00:08:54,456
step justices reserve for the rulings they

174
00:08:54,456 --> 00:08:56,215
most strongly oppose .

175
00:08:56,669 --> 00:08:59,717
So here is where it leaves you.

176
00:08:59,717 --> 00:09:02,765
Mandatory arbitration clauses,
with class-action waivers, are

177
00:09:02,765 --> 00:09:05,814
now a standard feature of American life

178
00:09:05,814 --> 00:09:08,862
— in the contracts for your phone,

179
00:09:08,862 --> 00:09:11,910
your bank account,
your streaming apps, and

180
00:09:11,910 --> 00:09:14,959
very often your employment . You have

181
00:09:14,959 --> 00:09:18,007
almost certainly agreed
to several of them,

182
00:09:18,007 --> 00:09:21,055
by doing nothing more than using a

183
00:09:21,055 --> 00:09:23,232
service or starting a job.

184
00:09:23,686 --> 00:09:26,506
Whether that is a good thing depends

185
00:09:26,506 --> 00:09:29,326
on which argument
you find more convincing,

186
00:09:29,326 --> 00:09:32,147
and that is a real debate, not

187
00:09:32,147 --> 00:09:34,967
a settled one . What is not

188
00:09:34,967 --> 00:09:37,787
in dispute is the mechanism. Two ordinary

189
00:09:37,787 --> 00:09:40,607
rights — to sue in open court,

190
00:09:40,607 --> 00:09:43,427
and to join with others — are

191
00:09:43,427 --> 00:09:46,247
now, for most people, waivable by a

192
00:09:46,247 --> 00:09:48,261
sentence almost no one reads.

193
00:09:48,715 --> 00:09:52,141
What can you actually do about it?

194
00:09:52,141 --> 00:09:55,567
Honestly, not much in the moment —

195
00:09:55,567 --> 00:09:58,993
the terms are rarely negotiable. But the

196
00:09:58,993 --> 00:10:02,419
argument itself is
not over. Lawmakers, regulators,

197
00:10:02,419 --> 00:10:05,845
and companies keep
fighting over where mandatory

198
00:10:05,845 --> 00:10:09,270
arbitration should apply
and where it should

199
00:10:09,270 --> 00:10:12,696
not, especially for the most serious kinds

200
00:10:12,696 --> 00:10:16,122
of claims. The line this series keeps

201
00:10:16,122 --> 00:10:19,548
chasing is, here too, still being drawn

202
00:10:19,548 --> 00:10:20,037
.

203
00:10:20,491 --> 00:10:23,702
And notice what makes this different from

204
00:10:23,702 --> 00:10:26,912
everything else in this series. No officer

205
00:10:26,912 --> 00:10:30,122
took anything. No
school punished anyone. The

206
00:10:30,122 --> 00:10:33,332
power here was handed over voluntarily, in

207
00:10:33,332 --> 00:10:36,542
the most ordinary act of modern life:

208
00:10:36,542 --> 00:10:39,752
tapping a button to make a screen

209
00:10:39,752 --> 00:10:40,669
go away.

210
00:10:41,123 --> 00:10:43,767
A thirty-dollar charge on a "free" phone

211
00:10:43,767 --> 00:10:46,411
ended up drawing one of the quietest

212
00:10:46,411 --> 00:10:49,054
but widest lines in modern law —

213
00:10:49,054 --> 00:10:51,698
the line between the rights you have

214
00:10:51,698 --> 00:10:54,342
and the rights you can sign away

215
00:10:54,342 --> 00:10:56,985
without realizing it . The Court did

216
00:10:56,985 --> 00:10:59,629
not take those rights from you. It

217
00:10:59,629 --> 00:11:02,273
said you were free to give them

218
00:11:02,273 --> 00:11:04,916
up. The fine print did the rest.

219
00:11:05,370 --> 00:11:08,399
We have now watched the state search

220
00:11:08,399 --> 00:11:11,428
you, track you, take your property, and

221
00:11:11,428 --> 00:11:14,457
police your speech — and watched you

222
00:11:14,457 --> 00:11:17,486
hand over rights yourself, by contract. In

223
00:11:17,486 --> 00:11:20,515
every case, the
same question keeps returning

224
00:11:20,515 --> 00:11:23,544
in a new costume: where is the

225
00:11:23,544 --> 00:11:26,573
line, and who gets to move it?

226
00:11:27,027 --> 00:11:29,971
The next case
moves that question somewhere

227
00:11:29,971 --> 00:11:32,915
more intimate than a phone or a

228
00:11:32,915 --> 00:11:35,859
contract. Not what you carry, or what

229
00:11:35,859 --> 00:11:38,803
you sign, but what is inside your

230
00:11:38,803 --> 00:11:41,747
body. When the police arrest you —

231
00:11:41,747 --> 00:11:44,691
before any trial, before any conviction —

232
00:11:44,691 --> 00:11:47,635
can they take a sample of your

233
00:11:47,635 --> 00:11:50,579
DNA, and keep it? That is next

234
00:11:50,579 --> 00:11:51,000
time.
